Date: Wed 10 Aug 2011
Source: Scottish Daily Record [edited]
http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/2011/08/10/action-needed-to-tackle-hepatitis-c-epidemic-in-scotland-demands-top-doctor-86908-23334505/


Act now to tackle an "epidemic" of hepatitis C, says a leading doctor
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Dr Roy Robertson, chair of the National Forum on Drug-Related Deaths,
said around 1000 new cases are recorded each year in Scotland. An
estimated 39 000 people in Scotland [population about 5 million -
Mod.CP] have hepatitis C.

Treatment services need improving and people need to be encouraged to
be tested, said Dr Robertson, a GP based in Edinburgh. He said:
"Hepatitis C is a hugely important epidemic [disease] and it's almost
entirely due to [illicit drug use]. Most of the epidemic in Scotland
has been amongst injecting drug users.

"We've always expected that this is going to be an increasing number
of cases over many years. Some people who get the virus can clear it
from their system and it's no longer a problem. Others go on having
the disease but don't get ill for many, many years." He said people
who used drugs and shared needles in the 1980s are starting to become
unwell from this virus [disease]. "Eventually the incubation period
elapses and people begin to manifest cirrhosis and advanced liver
failure and the death rate will undoubtedly increase over the next few
years," he added. Estimates indicate that the annual death toll from
hepatitis C-related causes in Scotland could be between 100 to 200 by
2015. "And that will continue, probably indefinitely, for the next
goodness-knows-how-many years," he added.

Dr Robertson, whose group helps to advise the Scottish Government,
called for investment in treatment services. He continued: "We treat
probably about 1000 cases per year in Scotland, which clearly isn't
enough, and we need much more in terms of treatment services provision
to reduce the size of the overall pool. For treatment services, now is
the time."

Dr Robertson said more treatment would cure more people, who could go
on to develop liver damage, and may slow the rate of the epidemic.
"Liver specialists are going to be overwhelmed. Also, I think,
treatment services are not terribly sympathetic and not terribly
supportive in some areas. And I think we could do a lot more to
provide better treatment services for a very difficult group of
patients."

Dr Saket Priyadarshi, lead clinician in addiction services for NHS
[National Health Service] Greater Glasgow and Clyde and vice-chair of
the National Forum on Drug-Related Deaths, said treating hepatitis C
now would save millions of pounds in health care in the future.

