HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Hepatitis C virus infection sometimes results in an acute symptomatic
illness. It can range in severity from a mild illness lasting a few
weeks to a serious, lifelong chronic condition that can lead to
cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer. A chronic hepatitis C
infection is when the infection lasts for longer than 6 months. The
course of the chronic infection varies considerably between people and
is unpredictable.

Hepatitis C virus is transmitted through contact with the blood of an
infected person. About 130-170 million people are chronically infected
with hepatitis C virus, and more than 350 000 people die from
hepatitis C-related liver diseases each year. Hepatitis C virus
infection is found worldwide. Countries with high rates of chronic
infection are Egypt (22 per cent), Pakistan (4.8 per cent), and China
(3.2 per cent). The main mode of transmission in these countries is
attributed to unsafe injections using contaminated equipment.

Following initial infection, about 80 per cent of people do not
exhibit any symptoms. Those people who are acutely symptomatic may
exhibit fever, fatigue, decreased appetite, nausea, vomiting,
abdominal pain, dark urine, grey-coloured faeces, joint pain, and
jaundice. When a chronically-infected person develops symptoms, it may
indicate advanced liver disease. Statistically, 60-70 per cent of
those with chronic infection develop chronic liver disease, 5-20 per
cent develop cirrhosis, and 1-5 per cent die from cirrhosis or liver
cancer. (WHO Fact sheet 164:
http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs164/en/index.html).

There are 6 genotypes of hepatitis C virus, which is an enveloped,
positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus of the family _Flaviviridae_.
Almost all people in the UK who have hepatitis C have genotype 1,
genotype 2, or genotype 3 virus. The different genotypes respond
differently to treatment, and it is possible to be infected with more
than one type of hepatitis C at the same time.

As the damage caused by the hepatitis C is usually very gradual, the
time at which people with hepatitis C start treatment may vary between
cases. The usual treatment involves administration of pegylated
interferon and/or ribavirin. The treatment clears the virus in almost
half of those infected with genotype 1, and about 80 per cent of those
infected with genotype 2 or 3. A course of treatment lasts 6-12
months, depending upon the hepatitis C virus genotype. It takes about
12 weeks to determine if this treatment is working. Side-effects from
these treatments can occur which may include tiredness, nausea,
headaches, and depression. New treatments are becoming available which
may improve outcomes.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Scotland can be accessed
at http://healthmap.org/r/00a8. - Mod.CP]
